  <p class="last-updated">Last updated March 2026</p>
  <h1>Cat Age Calculator</h1>
  <p class="page-desc">Convert your cat's age to human years using the veterinary age model. See the life stage, expected lifespan, and how indoor vs. outdoor lifestyle affects longevity.</p>

  <div class="calculator-box">
    <div class="calc-inputs">
      <div class="input-group">
        <label for="catAge">Cat's Age (years)</label>
        <input type="number" id="catAge" value="5" min="0" max="30" step="0.5" />
      </div>
      <div class="input-group">
        <label for="catType">Cat Type</label>
        <select id="catType">
          <option value="indoor" selected>Indoor</option>
          <option value="outdoor">Outdoor</option>
          <option value="both">Indoor/Outdoor</option>
        </select>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="calc-results">
      <div class="result-cards">
        <div class="result-card primary">
          <span class="result-label">Human Equivalent Age</span>
          <span class="result-value" id="humanAge">--</span>
        </div>
        <div class="result-card">
          <span class="result-label">Life Stage</span>
          <span class="result-value" id="lifeStage">--</span>
        </div>
        <div class="result-card">
          <span class="result-label">Average Life Expectancy</span>
          <span class="result-value" id="lifeExpectancy">--</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <AdUnit slot="calc-mid" format="rectangle" />

  <article class="content-section">
    <h2>How Cat Aging Works</h2>
    <p>Cats do not age at a constant rate compared to humans. Like dogs, cats mature very rapidly during their first two years of life and then age more gradually afterward. However, the aging pattern in cats is different from dogs in an important way: cat aging is not significantly affected by body size the way dog aging is. A Maine Coon and a Siamese cat age at roughly the same rate, unlike a Great Dane and a Chihuahua, which age very differently.</p>
    <p>The widely cited "one cat year equals seven human years" rule is a myth. A 1-year-old cat is not a 7-year-old child; it is closer to a 15-year-old teenager. By its first birthday, a cat has reached sexual maturity, grown to nearly full adult size, and developed the physical capabilities of a young adult human. The first year of a cat's life packs an extraordinary amount of development into a short period.</p>
    <p>The second year of a cat's life adds approximately 9 more human years, bringing a 2-year-old cat to roughly 24 in human equivalent terms. After age 2, the aging rate stabilizes at approximately 4 human years per cat year. This model, endorsed by the American Association of Feline Practitioners (AAFP) and the American Animal Hospital Association (AAHA), provides a much more accurate picture of feline aging than the old 7-to-1 rule.</p>
    <div class="formula-box">
      <code>Year 1 = 15 human years</code><br />
      <code>Year 2 = +9 human years (total: 24)</code><br />
      <code>Each year after 2 = +4 human years</code>
    </div>
    <p>Using this model, a 5-year-old cat is approximately 15 + 9 + (3 &times; 4) = 36 human years. A 10-year-old cat is about 15 + 9 + (8 &times; 4) = 56 human years. A 15-year-old cat is approximately 76 human years, and a 20-year-old cat is around 96 human years. These conversions help cat owners understand their pet's relative age and provide appropriate care for each life stage.</p>

    <h2>Cat Age to Human Age Chart</h2>
    <p>The table below converts cat ages from 1 to 20 years into human equivalent years and shows the corresponding life stage. This chart uses the veterinary-endorsed model described above.</p>
    <div class="table-responsive">
      <table class="info-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Cat Age</th><th>Human Years</th><th>Life Stage</th></tr>
        </thead>
